[[Category:ROOT/Exercises]]

== Adding/subtracting matrices == When adding or subtracting matrices you should add/subtract numbers in the same position, like this: :<math>\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 5 \\ 4 & 2 \\ \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 7 & 2 \\ 5 & 3 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 & 7 \\ 9 & 5 \\ \end{bmatrix}</math> :<math>\begin{bmatrix} 7 & 5 \\ 4 & -2 \\ \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 2 \\ -3 & 5 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 & 3 \\ 7 & -7 \\ \end{bmatrix}</math> Matrices can only be added/subtracted if they are of the same size.
== Multiplying matrices == When multiplying matrices by a number, you should multiply all the numbers inside them by that number, for example: :<math>2\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 \\ 4 & 2 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 6 \\ 8 & 4 \\ \end{bmatrix}</math>
{{BookCat}}

== Exercise ==
<onlyinclude>On an interactive ROOT session: Fill an array of 100&nbsp;000&nbsp;000 64Bit floating point numbers of the [[ROOT/Handling Data/ROOT Data Types|machine independent ROOT type]] <code>Double_t</code> with random numbers. Compute the mean of the array and print it to the console. Note the computation time.

'''Hint:''' You can get random real numbers by creating a pointer to an instance of the <code>TRandom</code> class. (The constructor takes one arbitrary integer as initialization.) Then you can call the method <code>TRandom::Rndm()</code> to get a simple pseudo random number uniformly distributed between 0 and 1. For example:

<source lang="cpp">
TRandom *R = new TRandom(time(0));  // create a pointer to a new instance of TRanom in the heap
cout << R->Rndm() << endl;
</source></onlyinclude>

== Solution ==
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|0|Int_t nums &#61; 100000000;  // random numbers to generate}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|1|TRandom *R &#61; new TRandom(time(0));}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|2|Double_t *seed &#61; new Double_t[nums];}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|3|for (Int_t i &#61; 0; i < nums; i++) &#123;}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLineStalled|seed[i] &#61; R->Rndm(); &#125;}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|4|// some 10-20 seconds later...}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|5|Double_t mean &#61; 0.0;}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|6|for (Int_t i &#61; 0; i < nums; i++) &#123;  // make use of pressing "uparrow" to recall the input of line 3}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLineStalled|mean +&#61; seed[i]; &#125;}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|7|// some 5-15 seconds later...}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|8|mean /&#61; nums;}}
{{ROOT/RootInputLine|9|cout << "mean &#61; " << mean << endl;}}
{{ROOT/RootOutput|mean &#61; 0.499963}}

